ion box begin no change\n| title = Nevada's 3rd congressional district, 2020\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = TBA\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = TBA\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Steve Brown\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Edward Bridges III\n| party = Independent American Party (Nevada)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==District 4==\n{{see also|Nevada's 4th congressional district}}\nThe 4th district covers the northern [[Las Vegas]] suburbs, including [[North Las Vegas]], and takes in rural central Nevada. The incumbent is Democrat [[Steven Horsford]], who was elected with 51.9% of the vote in 2018.<ref name=\"HPVT\" />\n\n===Democratic primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Declared=====\n*George Brucato, painting contractor<ref name=\"nv04d\">{{cite web |last1=Damon |first1=Anjeanette |last2=DeHaven |first2=James |title=FRIDAY DEADLINE: Here's who's running for federal, state and local offices in Reno-Sparks |url=https://www.rgj.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/02/candidates-file-offices-northern-nevada/4930208002/ |website=Reno Gazette Journal |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n*Chris Colley \n*Gabrielle D'Ayr, risk manager<ref name=\"NVcands\"/>\n*Jennifer Eason, progressive activist<ref name=\"nv04d\"/>\n*[[Steven Horsford]], incumbent U.S. Representative<ref name=\"nv04d\"/>\n*Gregory Kempton, teacher<ref name=\"nv04d\"/>\n\n====Primary results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Democratic primary results\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = George Brucato\n