{"title_page": "Baruel Mansion", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name         = Baruel Mansion\n| native_name  = Palacete Baruel\n| image                 = Palacete Baruel Santana.JPG\n| map_type              = \n| altitude              = \n| building_type         = [[Mansion]]\n| ren_cost              = \n| location              = [[Alto de Santana]] - [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo state|SP]]<br> [[Brazil]]\n| address               = 2677 Volunt\u00e1rios da P\u00e1tria street\n| client                = \n| owner                 = Cl\u00ednica de Fraturas ZN\n| coordinates           = {{coord|23|29|48|S|46|37|35|W|region:LI_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date            = 19th century (finished in 1879)\n| height                = \n| diameter              = \n| other_dimensions      = \n| floor_count           = \n| floor_area            = \n}}\n\n'''Baruel Mansion''' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: ''Palacete Baruel'') is a mansion built in the 19th century, located in [[Alto de Santana]], northern area of [[S\u00e3o Paulo city]]. \n{{Multiple image\n | align     = left\n | direction = vertical\n | width     = 130\n | image1    = Palacete Baruel 3.JPG\n | caption1  = \n | image2    = Palacete Baruel.JPG\n | caption2  = \n | image3    = Biblioteca Narbal Fontes 3.JPG\n | caption3  = House of Dona Maria, the current ''Narbal Fontes Library''.\n}}\nThe construction had been the headquarters of the Baruel [[Estate (land)|estate]],<ref>[http://www.prefeitura.sp.gov.br/cidade/secretarias/cultura/bibliotecas/bibliotecas_bairro/bibliotecas_m_z/narbalfontes/index.php?p=181 HIST\u00d3RICO DA BIBLIOTECA NARBAL FONTES (in Portuguese)]</ref> a farm where rice, [[beans]], [[Maize|corn]] and [[sugarcane]] were grown with slave labour.<ref>[https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/273/27301216.pdf Os Interiores Domesticos ap\u00f3s a Economia Exportadora Paulista (in Portuguese)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921235608/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/273/27301216.pdf |date=September 21, 2012 }}</ref> The wealth of the owner is perceived in the buildings that make up the area.<ref>[http://www.colegiosantana.com.br/instituicao/110anos.htm Hist\u00f3ria de Santana. (in Portuguese)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117131131/http://www.colegiosantana.com.br/instituicao/110anos.htm |date=January 17, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Estate (land)|estate]] was {{convert|24250|m2|ft2}} in area, and after the death of Mr. Baruel the property was divided and sold in lots. The farm included the house of Dona Maria, daughter of Mr. Baruel, built in 1925, which today houses the ''Narbal Fontes Library''.\n\nThe Baruel were a traditional and influential family of [[Santana (S\u00e3o Paulo)|Santana]]. Near the farm, in the current Volunt\u00e1rios da P\u00e1tria street is located in the ''Chapel of Santa Cruz'', built in 1895 by Pedro Doll and the Baruel family.\n\nBuilt in the [[Architecture of Normandy|Norman]] style, the mansion is considered a historic site, it saves time and remnants of the neighbourhood. It has never been inhabited. Currently the building is a [[physiotherapy]] [[clinic]].\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Houses in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Castles in Brazil]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name         = Baruel Mansion\n| native_name  = Palacete Baruel\n| image                 = Palacete Baruel Santana.JPG\n| map_type              = \n| altitude              = \n| building_type         = [[Mansion]]\n| ren_cost              = \n| location              = [[Alto de Santana]] - [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo state|SP]]<br> [[Brazil]]\n| address               = 2677 Volunt\u00e1rios da P\u00e1tria street\n| client                = \n| owner                 = Cl\u00ednica de Fraturas ZN\n| coordinates           = {{coord|23|29|48|S|46|37|35|W|region:LI_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date            = 19th century (finished in 1879)\n| height                = \n| diameter              = \n| other_dimensions      = \n| floor_count           = \n| floor_area            = \n}}\n\n'''Baruel Mansion''' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: ''Palacete Baruel'') is a mansion built in the 19th century, located in [[Alto de Santana]], northern area of [[S\u00e3o Paulo city]]. \n{{Multiple image\n | align     = left\n | direction = vertical\n | width     = 130\n | image1    = Palacete Baruel 3.JPG\n | caption1  = \n | image2    = Palacete Baruel.JPG\n | caption2  = \n | image3    = Biblioteca Narbal Fontes 3.JPG\n | caption3  = House of Dona Maria, the current ''Narbal Fontes Library''.\n}}\nThe construction had been the headquarters of the Baruel [[Estate (land)|estate]],<ref>[http://www.prefeitura.sp.gov.br/cidade/secretarias/cultura/bibliotecas/bibliotecas_bairro/bibliotecas_m_z/narbalfontes/index.php?p=181 HIST\u00d3RICO DA BIBLIOTECA NARBAL FONTES (in Portuguese)]</ref> a farm where rice, [[beans]], [[Maize|corn]] and [[sugarcane]] were grown with slave labour.<ref>[http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/273/27301216.pdf Os Interiores Domesticos ap\u00f3s a Economia Exportadora Paulista (in Portuguese)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921235608/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/273/27301216.pdf |date=September 21, 2012 }}</ref> The wealth of the owner is perceived in the buildings that make up the area.<ref>[http://www.colegiosantana.com.br/instituicao/110anos.htm Hist\u00f3ria de Santana. (in Portuguese)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117131131/http://www.colegiosantana.com.br/instituicao/110anos.htm |date=January 17, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Estate (land)|estate]] was {{convert|24250|m2|ft2}} in area, and after the death of Mr. Baruel the property was divided and sold in lots. The farm included the house of Dona Maria, daughter of Mr. Baruel, built in 1925, which today houses the ''Narbal Fontes Library''.\n\nThe Baruel were a traditional and influential family of [[Santana (S\u00e3o Paulo)|Santana]]. Near the farm, in the current Volunt\u00e1rios da P\u00e1tria street is located in the ''Chapel of Santa Cruz'', built in 1895 by Pedro Doll and the Baruel family.\n\nBuilt in the [[Architecture of Normandy|Norman]] style, the mansion is considered a historic site, it saves time and remnants of the neighbourhood. It has never been inhabited. Currently the building is a [[physiotherapy]] [[clinic]].\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Houses in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Castles in Brazil]]\n\n{{Brazil-struct-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Logan", "label": "safe", "comment": "bad link repair", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baruel_Mansion"}
{"title_page": "Fanum d'Aron", "text_new": "{{Infobox ancient site\n | name\t\t\t=\tFanum d'Aron\n | native_name\t\t=\t''Fanum d'Aron''\n | image\t\t=\tFanum d'Aron, Aurillac 2.jpeg\n | map_type\t\t=\tFrance\n | relief\t\t=\tYes\n | altitude_m\t\t=\t639\n | caption\t\t=\tThe ruins of ''Fanum d'Aron'', circa 2014.\n | coordinates\t\t=\t{{coord | 44.915716 | 2.421396\n | format\t\t=\tdms\n | display\t\t=\tinline,title}}\n | r\u00e9f\u00e9rence\t\t=\t\n | region\t\t=\t[[Auvergne]]\n | cultures\t\t=\t[[Arverni]], [[Gallo-Roman]]\n | epochs\t\t=\t[[Classical Antiquity]]\n | abandoned\t\t=\t[[3rd century|3rd century CE]]\n | type\t\t\t=\t[[Fanum]] ([[Romano-Celtic Temple]])\n | height\t\t=\t\n | diameter\t\t=\t18 m (59 ft)<ref name=\"RACF\">\n{{\ncite journal\n| last = Mitton\n| first = Claire\n| title = The Arverni and Vellavi's sanctuaries outside the capitals, from the 1st Century BC to the 4th Century AD: a typological and a spatial approach.\n| journal = Revue arch\u00e9ologique du Centre de la France\n| volume = Tome 45-46\n| issue = 2006-2007\n| pages = \n| publisher = OpenEdition Journals\n| date = 8 April 2008\n| url = http://journals.openedition.org/racf/680\n| accessdate = 25 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\n | material\t\t=\n | condition\t\t=\tRuined\n | public_access\t=\t\n | ownership\t\t=\tPrivate\n | excavations\t\t=\t1977 - 1978\n | built\t\t=\t[[1st century|1st century CE]]\n | designation1\t\t=\tMonument historique\n | designation1_date\t=\t20 November 1980\n | location\t\t=\t[[Aron]]{{dn|date=April 2020}}, [[Aurillac]], [[Cantal]], [[Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]], [[France]]}}\n\n'''Fanum d'Aron''' is a [[fanum]], or [[Romano-Celtic temple]], located in [[Aurillac]], a French commune in the [[Auvergne]] region.<ref name=MC>\n{{\ncite web\n| url = https://www.pop.culture.gouv.fr/notice/merimee/PA00093469\n| title = Temple gallo-romain de type fanum\n| accessdate = 25 April 2020\n| publisher = [[Minist\u00e8re de la Culture]]\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== Site and status ==\nDiscovered in 1970 in the southwest of Aurillac, the temple was excavated from May 1977 through the end of 1978 and added to the ''[[monuments historiques]]'' registry in 1980. It is situated in what is now a small municipal garden, between a pavilion and the Lescudilier industrial zone (cadastre BE n\u00b0360).<ref name=MC/><ref name=CDA>\n{{\ncite journal\n| last = Poursat\n| first = Jean-Claude\n| title = Circonscription d'Auvergne\n| journal = Gallia\n| volume = Tome 37\n| issue = fascicule 2\n| pages = 472-474\n| date = 1979\n| url = https://www.persee.fr/doc/galia_0016-4119_1979_num_37_2_1616\n| access-date=25 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== History ==\nSalvage excavations have recovered a number of artifacts from the site, such as coins, eight [[acanthus (plant)|acanthus-leafed]] [[Classical_order#Elements|column capitals]] (four of which feature sculpted heads representing the Sun and Moon), as well as a fluted column barrel fragment and [[terracotta]] [[antefix|antefixes]].<ref name=CDA/> These objects establish that the temple would have been in use from the [[first century|1st]] to [[third century|3rd centuries CE]].<ref name=RACF/><ref name=CDA/>\n\nSome artifacts and architectural elements from the site are kept on display at the Aurillac Museum of Art and Archeology (''[http://musees.aurillac.fr/index.php/2017/06/19/tete-de-meduse/ Le mus\u00e9e d'art et d'arch\u00e9ologie d'Aurillac]''), along with a model reconstruction of the fanum.\n\n== Architecture ==\nThe fanum's layout is a circular chamber ''([[cella]])'' surrounded by a sixteen-sided polygonal [[ambulatory]] or gallery. The angles of the polygon are marked by the bases of columns (eight of which are found in-place). The complex appears to have had a courtyard encircled by a perimeter wall that was discovered through sondage, towards the northwest. The wall is 55 meters (~180.5 ft) from the fanum, with a northwest-northeast orientation erected over a length of 84 meters (~275.6 ft). There is also vestiges of a partially exposed, square enclosure southeast of the fanum, whose sides are 29 meters (~95 ft) long.<ref name=RACF/><ref name=CDA/>\n\n''Fanum d'Aron'' appears uncommon in [[Arverni]] and [[Vellavi]] territory for having a polygonal rather than quadrangular ambulatory, and unique for the ambulatory being of sixteen sides. Another fanum found at [[Mauriac, Cantal|Mauriac]] (Cantal) can be compared for appearing to have had a round ''cella'' and decagonal ambulatory. This uncommon round ''cella'' with polygonal ambulatory plan seems to be more typical of Western Gaul than elsewhere, as it is also found in examples at [[Saint-Gervais, Vend\u00e9e|Saint-Gervais]] (Vend\u00e9e) and  [[Chassenon]] (Charente).<ref name=CDA/>\n\n== Related sites ==\nA prospection of the Cantal ''d\u00e9partement'' made by Alphonse Vinati\u00e9 (1924 - 2005), a local archaeologist, made it possible to identify three other ancient sanctuaries in [[Landeyrat]] and [[Allanche]]<ref name=SEL>\n{{\ncite journal\n| last = Calbris\n| first = Maxime\n| title = Changes in Places of Worship in the Ancient Urban Zone at Mathoni\u00e8re, in Allanche (Cantal): An Analysis of Pedestrian, Arial, and Geophysical Surveys\n| journal = Si\u00e8cles (en ligne)\n| volume = 48\n| issue = 2020\n| publisher = OpenEdition Journals\n| date = 24 February 2020\n| url = http://journals.openedition.org/siecles/6279\n| accessdate = 25 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>, as well as possible sites in [[Celles, Cantal|Celles]], [[Charmensac]], and [[Mauriac, Cantal|Mauriac]] Vernols.<ref name=RACF/>\n\n== References == \n{{reflist}}\n== Further Reading ==\n* \u00ab Destruction \u00e0 Aurillac du seul sanctuaire gallo-romain de Haute-Auvergne \u00bb, Genevi\u00e8ve Charbonneau, [[1979]], in ''Revue Arch\u00e9ologia'', n\u00b0 131, p. 36-53,\n* \u00ab D\u00e9couverte d\u2019un temple gallo-romain \u00e0 Aurillac. Fouille de sauvetage \u00e0 Lescudilier-Aron \u00bb, Genevi\u00e8ve Degoul , [[1977]], in ''Revue de la Haute-Auvergne'', p. 273-331,\n* \u00ab Les fouilles du fanum polygonal d\u2019Aron \u00bb, Odette Lapeyre, R\u00e9gine Roche et L\u00e9once Bouyssou, [[1988]], in ''Revue de la Haute-Auvergne'', n\u00b0 51, p. 37-98. Premi\u00e8re publication en 1985 dans la \"Suppl\u00e9ment\" au ''Bulletin du Groupe de recherches historiques et arch\u00e9ologiques de la vall\u00e9e de la Sum\u00e8ne''.\n\n=== See Also ===\n* [[Arverni]]\n* [[Celtic polytheism]]\n* [[Gallo-Roman culture]]\n* [[Gauls]]\n\n{{Celts|state=collapsed}}\n{{France topics}}\n\n[[Category:Celtic archaeological sites]]\n[[Category:Celtic religion]]\n[[Category:Gallo-Roman religion]]\n[[Category:Gauls]]\n[[Category:Averni]]\n[[Category:Roman sites in France]]\n[[Category:Ancient Roman temples]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of France]]\n[[Category:Monuments historiques of Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ancient site\n | name\t\t\t=\tFanum d'Aron\n | native_name\t\t=\t''Fanum d'Aron''\n | image\t\t=\tFanum d'Aron, Aurillac 2.jpeg\n | map_type\t\t=\tFrance\n | relief\t\t=\tYes\n | altitude_m\t\t=\t639\n | caption\t\t=\tThe ruins of ''Fanum d'Aron'', circa 2014.\n | coordinates\t\t=\t{{coord | 44.915716 | 2.421396\n | format\t\t=\tdms\n | display\t\t=\tinline,title}}\n | r\u00e9f\u00e9rence\t\t=\t\n | region\t\t=\t[[Auvergne]]\n | cultures\t\t=\t[[Arverni]], [[Gallo-Roman]]\n | epochs\t\t=\t[[Classical Antiquity]]\n | abandoned\t\t=\t[[3rd century|3rd century CE]]\n | type\t\t\t=\t[[Fanum]] ([[Romano-Celtic Temple]])\n | height\t\t=\t\n | diameter\t\t=\t18 m (59 ft)<ref name=\"RACF\">\n{{\ncite journal\n| last = Mitton\n| first = Claire\n| title = The Arverni and Vellavi's sanctuaries outside the capitals, from the 1st Century BC to the 4th Century AD: a typological and a spatial approach.\n| journal = Revue arch\u00e9ologique du Centre de la France\n| volume = Tome 45-46\n| issue = 2006-2007\n| pages = \n| publisher = OpenEdition Journals\n| date = 8 April 2008\n| url = http://journals.openedition.org/racf/680\n| accessdate = 25 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\n | material\t\t=\n | condition\t\t=\tRuined\n | public_access\t=\t\n | ownership\t\t=\tPrivate\n | excavations\t\t=\t1977 - 1978\n | built\t\t=\t[[1st century|1st century CE]]\n | designation1\t\t=\tMonument historique\n | designation1_date\t=\t20 November 1980\n | location\t\t=\t[[Aron]]{{dn|date=April 2020}}, [[Aurillac]], [[Cantal]], [[Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]], [[France]]}}\n\n'''Fanum d'Aron''' is a [[fanum]], or [[Romano-Celtic temple]], located in [[Aurillac]], a French commune in the [[Auvergne]] region.<ref name=MC>\n{{\ncite web\n| url = https://www.pop.culture.gouv.fr/notice/merimee/PA00093469\n| title = Temple gallo-romain de type fanum\n| accessdate = 25 April 2020\n| publisher = [[Minist\u00e8re de la Culture]]\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== Site and status ==\nDiscovered in 1970 in the southwest of Aurillac, the temple was excavated from May 1977 through the end of 1978 and added to the ''[[monuments historiques]]'' registry in 1980. It is situated in what is now a small municipal garden, between a pavilion and the Lescudilier industrial zone (cadastre BE n\u00b0360).<ref name=MC/><ref name=CDA>\n{{\ncite journal\n| last = Poursat\n| first = Jean-Claude\n| title = Circonscription d'Auvergne\n| journal = Gallia\n| volume = Tome 37\n| issue = fascicule 2\n| pages = 472-474\n| date = 1979\n| url = https://www.persee.fr/doc/galia_0016-4119_1979_num_37_2_1616\n| access-date=25 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== History ==\nSalvage excavations have recovered a number of artifacts from the site, such as coins, eight [[acanthus (plant)|acanthus-leafed]] [[Classical_order#Elements|column capitals]] (four of which feature sculpted heads representing the Sun and Moon), as well as a fluted column barrel fragment and [[terracotta]] [[antefix|antefixes]].<ref name=CDA/> These objecs establish that the temple would have been in use from the [[first century|1st]] to [[third century|3rd centuries CE]].<ref name=RACF/><ref name=CDA/>\n\nSome artifacts and architectural elements from the site are kept on display at the Aurillac Museum of Art and Archeology (''[http://musees.aurillac.fr/index.php/2017/06/19/tete-de-meduse/ Le mus\u00e9e d'art et d'arch\u00e9ologie d'Aurillac]''), along with a model reconstruction of the fanum.\n\n== Architecture ==\nThe fanum's layout is a circular chamber ''([[cella]])'' surrounded by a sixteen-sided polygonal [[ambulatory]] or gallery. The angles of the polygon are marked by the bases of columns (eight of which are found in-place). The complex appears to have had a courtyard encircled by a perimeter wall that was discovered through sondage, towards the northwest. The wall is 55 meters (~180.5 ft) from the fanum, with a northwest-northeast orientation erected over a length of 84 meters (~275.6 ft). There is also vestiges of a partially exposed, square enclosure southeast of the fanum, whose sides are 29 meters (~95 ft) long.<ref name=RACF/><ref name=CDA/>\n\n''Fanum d'Aron'' appears uncommon in [[Arverni]] and [[Vellavi]] territory for having a polygonal rather than quadrangular ambulatory, and unique for the ambulatory being of sixteen sides. Another fanum found at [[Mauriac, Cantal|Mauriac]] (Cantal) can be compared for appearing to have had a round ''cella'' and decagonal ambulatory. This uncommon round ''cella'' with polygonal ambulatory plan seems to be more typical of Western Gaul than elsewhere, as it is also found in examples at [[Saint-Gervais, Vend\u00e9e|Saint-Gervais]] (Vend\u00e9e) and  [[Chassenon]] (Charente).<ref name=CDA/>\n\n== Related sites ==\nA prospection of the Cantal ''d\u00e9partement'' made by Alphonse Vinati\u00e9 (1924 - 2005), a local archaeologist, made it possible to identify three other ancient sanctuaries in [[Landeyrat]] and [[Allanche]]<ref name=SEL>\n{{\ncite journal\n| last = Calbris\n| first = Maxime\n| title = Changes in Places of Worship in the Ancient Urban Zone at Mathoni\u00e8re, in Allanche (Cantal): An Analysis of Pedestrian, Arial, and Geophysical Surveys\n| journal = Si\u00e8cles (en ligne)\n| volume = 48\n| issue = 2020\n| publisher = OpenEdition Journals\n| date = 24 February 2020\n| url = http://journals.openedition.org/siecles/6279\n| accessdate = 25 April 2020\n}}\n</ref>, as well as possible sites in [[Celles, Cantal|Celles]], [[Charmensac]], and [[Mauriac, Cantal|Mauriac]] Vernols.<ref name=RACF/>\n\n== References == \n{{reflist}}\n== Further Reading ==\n* \u00ab Destruction \u00e0 Aurillac du seul sanctuaire gallo-romain de Haute-Auvergne \u00bb, Genevi\u00e8ve Charbonneau, [[1979]], in ''Revue Arch\u00e9ologia'', n\u00b0 131, p. 36-53,\n* \u00ab D\u00e9couverte d\u2019un temple gallo-romain \u00e0 Aurillac. Fouille de sauvetage \u00e0 Lescudilier-Aron \u00bb, Genevi\u00e8ve Degoul , [[1977]], in ''Revue de la Haute-Auvergne'', p. 273-331,\n* \u00ab Les fouilles du fanum polygonal d\u2019Aron \u00bb, Odette Lapeyre, R\u00e9gine Roche et L\u00e9once Bouyssou, [[1988]], in ''Revue de la Haute-Auvergne'', n\u00b0 51, p. 37-98. Premi\u00e8re publication en 1985 dans la \"Suppl\u00e9ment\" au ''Bulletin du Groupe de recherches historiques et arch\u00e9ologiques de la vall\u00e9e de la Sum\u00e8ne''.\n\n=== See Also ===\n* [[Arverni]]\n* [[Celtic polytheism]]\n* [[Gallo-Roman culture]]\n* [[Gauls]]\n\n{{Celts|state=collapsed}}\n{{France topics}}\n\n[[Category:Celtic archaeological sites]]\n[[Category:Celtic religion]]\n[[Category:Gallo-Roman religion]]\n[[Category:Gauls]]\n[[Category:Averni]]\n[[Category:Roman sites in France]]\n[[Category:Ancient Roman temples]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of France]]\n[[Category:Monuments historiques of Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]]\n", "name_user": "Uiscefada", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo: \"objecs\" > objects", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fanum_d%27Aron"}
